label chapter2:

    # [Scene: Boathouse | Morning]

    scene bg ch2_c4ca42_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Sparse piano with a low, sustained cello undertone]
    "You push the boathouse door and the damp air folds around you—salt and wet rope and the faint, oily tang of the harbor. The wood under your boots sighs the way it always does: swollen, slow,"
    "familiar. Elias is already there, hunched over the bench, sleeves rolled, a leather-bound sketchbook splayed like an open map. His hair hangs damp against his forehead; a single braid loops at the nape of his neck."
    "The brass of his pocket watch glints when he turns."
    show elias_voss at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elias_voss "You're late—by a minute. Good. I hate thinking alone."
    "His smile is quiet. There's coffee steam curling from two mismatched mugs; the smell is bitter and grounding. You let the boat smell and that small sweetness of shared focus steady you before the list of tasks in your head pulls taut again."
    "You sit opposite him, fingers finding a tide chart you drew last month. The paper is softened at the creases, the ink blurred where rain found it. You trace the high-tide line automatically—it's a small, private ritual: read the map, read the town."

    elias_voss "Look. Oyster beds here, in rotated rows to slow the current. Tidal garden tucked against the southeast slip—uses the outflow instead of fighting it. If we pilot it small, we don't need permits the region will hold up. Could be a demonstrator—workshops in renovated storefronts after that."
    "You study his sketches: neat hatch marks for beds, little arrows for water flow, a soft plan of storefronts with raised thresholds. His handwriting curls like the edge of a shell; practical, but with room for something like hope."
    "Your mind lists logistics before you let the word hope settle: oyster seed sources, baskets, volunteer hours, small motors for aeration if the oxygen dips, materials for lifting thresholds, who will man the workshops, insurance. You"
    "set down your mug and let the practical catalog form like a tide pool: clear, immediate, alive with small organisms of detail."
    show maya_ortega at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ortega "Piloting is more defensible than a big build. We can show results in a season, not in a year. What's your timeline?"

    elias_voss "Two months for the first bed—if we can get volunteers and a small boat motor donated. Renovations—phased. One storefront at a time. We don't need everything at once."
    "There is a cadence to your exchange—ideas passed back and forth like shells across a bench—each of you fitting your strengths into the other's gaps. His sketches become your checklist; your tide annotations sharpen his spatial thinking. Together, the plan feels less fragile."

    menu:
        "Ask him about funding quietly":
            "You lower your voice and ask where the money comes from—small grants, a local fundraiser? Elias's face tightens the slightest degree; he says, 'Rely on local pledges first. Keep it independent.' You jot down possible microgrant sources, the sound of pen against paper louder than the rain."
        "Focus on volunteer logistics":
            "You map out who you know—Rosa's crews, Luca, the harbor apprentices. Elias nods, relief softening his features. 'If we can promise steady shifts, we can make physical labor the currency,' he says, already sketching a volunteer roster."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues."
    "The air holds its own quiet argument: how to keep the town's work of repair from becoming the town's debt. Your jaw tightens as you think of the council, of votes decided in boardrooms that never"
    "smelled like wet rope. You keep the list moving—materials, people, timelines—because thinking ahead is a way to keep your worry from spilling outward."
    "Footsteps slap on the dock. Rosa arrives as if the tide has carried her in—boots caked with mud, braid wound with shells that click when she moves. Her face is the weather: sun-creased and fierce."
    show rosa_delgado at center:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_delgado "News. There's a council session tonight. Tamsin's pushing something big. Word is—developer money. Rapid-build seawall, pre-fab sections. Quick, clean, paid for."
    "The words land like a stone dropped into a shallow pool. The ripples are immediate: you can see them on the surface of everything you have been planning. The boathouse seems to narrow, the bench lengthened into a place where history and policy and pressure press against you."

    maya_ortega "How fast are we talking—construction season, or 'overnight'?"

    rosa_delgado "They want to move before the next storm window. Contracts signed fast. They say it shields the town—and brings private investment. People hungry for work will like the paycheck."
    "Elias Voss stops sketching. For a moment the sound of the pencil on paper fills the space between you, fragile as a tide line. His mouth makes a thin line."

    elias_voss "If it's that fast, they lock out community input. They can box us out—no pilot, no staged adaptation. We need to show capability before they roll in concrete."
    "You feel the familiar quickening behind your ribs—not the frenetic kind but the sharpened readiness of someone who has stood in floodwater and watched things you love tilt. Everything practical you carry—lists, sketches, tide observations—becomes a"
    "kind of armor. Your chest caves a little at the thought of Tamsin's slate blazer and clipped efficiency, of decisions made for the good of some abstract greater whole while the town's texture is sanded away."

    rosa_delgado "We can mobilize a hearing. Bring data, bring kids' voices. Bring people who'd be hurt by a wall that severs their docks. But it's tonight. We have to move now."
    "You hold her gaze and in it the many small households you have sworn to protect float up—Luca's laugh at dinner, Henrik's tired smile, the bakery that drapes sandbags like bunting in storms. Your mouth tastes like a planning meeting that has been postponed too long."

    maya_ortega "We do a pilot—harbor first. Working models that reduce erosion and create livelihood. If we can have evidence of ecological and economic benefits, we can argue for a hybrid approach. We can ask the council for a six-month delay to evaluate."

    elias_voss "Six months is asking a lot. But—if we can promise immediate labor and a plan, we might buy time. If we bring in local businesses—workshops that double as reinforcements—people see jobs and protection."
    "The conversation continues, tentative and meticulous. You and Elias trade contingencies; he raises his concerns about funding streams drying up if the developer locks the site. You counter with steps: what materials can be salvaged, who"
    "can donate time, which storefronts are structurally sound enough for raised thresholds. Each point is a small argument against the inevitability implied by the word 'rapid.'"

    elias_voss "I can reach out to the regional co-op—soft letters, a few named contacts. It won't be a check today, but it's a start."

    maya_ortega "I'll draft the mobilization schedule and a short packet we can hand to the council. Rosa will organize the hearing crowd. We can do this without asking for a lot up front."
    "Your hand moves to highlight a vulnerable stretch on the tide chart—the corner where storms pick and pry at the boardwalk. As your fingers hover, Elias's hand slips in to point to the same line. For"
    "an instant your fingers brush; the contact is small, electric in the hush of planning. The bench, the tide map, and the harbor smell condense into that narrow space between what you can do and what"
    "you might lose."

    menu:
        "Let the brush pass as business":
            "You pull your hand back and keep talking, shielding the moment with detail. Your voice is steady, but internally you catalog the contact: warm, quick, a small permission you don't name. Elias clears his throat and redirects to materials."
        "Allow the pause to linger":
            "You let your hand stay, letting the moment extend. Elias meets your eyes; a silence blooms that holds a simpler, quieter language. He exhales, and the plan resumes with a softness to the cadence of his speech."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues."
    "Low, anxious, methodical—the mood of the room is all of those. The day unfolds like a careful tide: incremental, inevitable, full of small choices that will add up to something larger. Rosa's news presses on the"
    "edges of every sentence you make, a constant reminder that time is thinner than you want it to be."

    rosa_delgado "If Tamsin's going to pitch it as survival, we need to counter that narrative. People respond to immediacy. We show them we can create jobs and protection without erasing the town."

    maya_ortega "We'll show them both. Proof, not promises. Keep the message simple—livelihoods, dignity, local control."

    elias_voss "And if they don't listen?"
    "The question hangs. For a beat you imagine the town divided—pilings of concrete where fishermen once mended nets, a boardwalk truncated by a wall no one asked for. That image gnaws at the edges of your optimism."

    maya_ortega "Then we make the demonstrator so visible they can't ignore it. We show it's cheaper in the long run, that it preserves the character people love. We show them people can be part of the solution."
    "The three of you bend back into work: lists, timelines, contacts. The talk is slow, precise—less the spark of revolution than the patient assembling of tools. You feel the rising pressure of a decision on the"
    "horizon, the way a low cloud gathers before a storm; it's not panic, but an insistence that demands clarity."
    hide elias_voss
    hide maya_ortega
    hide rosa_delgado

    scene bg ch2_c4ca42_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Single cello note repeats, sustaining, then resolves into a delicate, uncertain chord]
    "You push a fresh sheet of paper toward Elias and Rosa—sketches, a proposed schedule for the pilot, a list of people to call. Your pen hovers, then moves. The plan is a lever; the rumor of the rapid-build seawall is a weight on the other side."
    "You stand up to stretch, the bench creaking under your weight. Outside, the harbor breathes; inside, you can hear the town tightening as decisions near."
    "A page-turn sits in your chest again—only this time it hums with other people's voices. Tonight's council; the rumor of quick money; the possibility that you and Elias are on the same side of more than"
    "strategy. The room holds all of it—a fragile, practical hope and a heavy, bureaucratic threat."
    "You fold the tide chart along the line you've marked, feeling the paper's grain under your fingertips, and let the plan settle into a shape you can carry to the council."

    scene bg ch2_c4ca42_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Piano returns, simple and unresolved]
    "A quiet resolve forms in you—practical steps, visible work, a plea for time. The decision is not yet made. The night waits; the council waits; the town waits."

